@remark *********************************************************************

@node IntroductionNode "ScreenMaster: Introduction"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Introduction@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

@{i}Welcome to ScreenMaster!@{ui}@{par}

I believe you'll find ScreenMaster to be one of the most comprehensive
public screen management systems around.@{par}

If you're not clear on the subject of public screens, what they are
and what they can do for you, read @{"About Public Screens" link PubScreensNode}.@{par}

The heart of all this wizardry is actually not the ScreenMaster
program at all, but the ARexx host ScreenDaemon. This provides a
complete set of commands to control public screens via the ARexx
language that comes with Workbench 2 and above. In fact, apart from
the commodity interface, ARexx is the only way to communicate with
ScreenDaemon; it does not open a window.@{par}

Mouse jockeys need not fear, however, for ScreenMaster will happily
present you with a graphical interface for controlling the daemon. It
will even help you automate the process of opening public screens by
writing the ARexx scripts that will do this for you.@{par}

Not being one to leave anything wanting, I've added ScreenBacker to
this package. ScreenBacker can add backdrop patterns and customized
menus to public screens. The menus automatically include some screen
management functions, plus an extensible set of items that you can
configure to run your favourite programs, just like the Workbench
Tools menu. ScreenBacker, like ScreenDaemon, is an ARexx host and does
not have a window of its own. It is also a commodity.@{par}

To make things even easier, ScreenMenuEd provides a graphical user
interface that you can use to create and save the custom menu
definitions that ScreenBacker reads.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node PubScreensNode "ScreenMaster: About Public Screens"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}About Public Screens@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}====================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

@{fg shine}The Workbench Screen and Custom Screens.@{fg text}@{par}

If you've used your Amiga at all you'll know it can display multiple
screens. You'll have seen the Workbench screen that Workbench and most
applications open their windows on, and custom screens opened by
applications such as paint programs. By opening a custom screen, the
program gains complete control over the number of colours available
and the screen's size, amongst other things. However, you cannot
generally share a custom screen between two applications.@{par}

@{fg shine}Public Screens.@{fg text}@{par}

With the release of Workbench 2, Commodore introduced a third type of
screen, the public screen. Programs can happily share a public screen
that one of them, or the user, has opened. Programs for Workbench 2
and above often have some way for you to tell them which screen to
open on, usually using tooltypes or on the Shell command line. And
programs that open their own screens often have an option to make that
screen public.@{par}

This opens up the possibility for the user to open his or her own
public screen and direct applications to it, thus freeing up the
Workbench screen from its usual clutter of windows. Unfortunately,
Commodore in their wisdom did not include the requisite public screen
manager, which is where ScreenMaster steps in. And by the way, no, you
can't redirect Workbench itself on to a public screen.@{par}

@{fg shine}The Default Public Screen.@{fg text}@{par}

At all times one public screen is special by being the default public
screen. This is the screen that application windows open on when they
haven't asked for a specific screen. Normally, the Workbench screen is
the default, but you can change this with ScreenMaster. By opening a
new public screen and making it the default, you can make most
Workbench 2 aware programs open on that screen.@{par}

@{fg shine}PopPubScreen and Shanghai.@{fg text}@{par}

PopPubScreen and Shanghai are flags, values that are either on or off.
When PopPubScreen is on, any window opening on a public screen (called
a visitor window) causes that screen to be "popped" to the front. This
is very convenient most of the time, as you can direct a program to
your brand new public screen and have it bring that screen to the
front for you.@{par}

The Shanghai flag is provided for use with older programs that don't
know about public screens. They always end up on the Workbench screen
and have no option for you to tell them otherwise. By turning Shanghai
on, you can force these programs to open on the current default public
screen, which can, of course, be one you have opened yourself.@{par}

@{fg shine}Uses of Public Screens.@{fg text}@{par}

To help let the idea settle in, I'll give some examples of why you
might want to open your own public screen.@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} To provide maximum screen space for a program, but still let you
quickly get to your uncluttered Workbench to manipulate files and
drawers.@{par}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} To open a program on a screen with fewer colours than your Workbench,
so that it works faster (eg. a Shell window), or on a screen with more
colours so that it looks better (eg. Amiga Mosaic).@{par}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} To run an old program on a simple, low resolution screen, either
because it can't cope with your high resolution Workbench screen, or
because it insists on using the Topaz 8 font, which is too small at
high resolutions.@{par}

@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node FeaturesNode "ScreenMaster: Features"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Features@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Works with AmigaOS 2.04 and above, takes advantage of OS3 if
present.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Complete control over the specification of new public screens.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Can add backdrop patterns/pictures to public screens.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Can add menus to public screens, with screen management functions,
plus user-defined Tools menu for launching applications.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Option to AutoClose screen when all visitor windows have left.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Control over open public screens: close screen, make default, move
to front/back, display screen attributes.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Control over system public screen flags: PopPubScreen and Shanghai.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} ARexx host provides comprehensive public screen management
facilities for your ARexx scripts.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Save screen specification from the GUI to an automatically generated
ARexx script, just double click to open the screen again.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Can be started from Workbench or Shell.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Commodity option, with user-definable popup hotkey.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Font-sensitive gadget layout in resizeable windows using either
@{"BGUI" link BGUINode} or @{"MUI" link MUINode} systems.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Opens on the default public screen, optionally on a named one.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} All gadgets have keyboard shortcuts.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} AmigaGuide documentation, available on-line.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Installer script included.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Locale support for presenting all text and messages in the user's
preferred language, plus the option to override and specify the
language.@{par}

@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node RequirementsNode "ScreenMaster: Requirements"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Requirements@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}============@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

If you wish to use @{"ScreenDaemon" link "ScreenDaemon.guide/RequirementsNode"} or @{"ScreenBacker" link ScreenBacker.guide/RequirementsNode} without ScreenMaster,
see the appropriate guide for the specific requirements of those
components.@{par}

ScreenMaster requires:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} AmigaOS 2.04 / Kickstart V37 or higher.@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} ARexxMast to be running. @{i}(inter-process communication)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

The BGUI version requires:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} bgui.library V38 or higher. @{i}(windows, gadgets, etc)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

The MUI version requires:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} MUI V2.3 or higher. @{i}(windows, gadgets, etc)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

ScreenMaster also requires that ScreenDaemon be running in order to
open and close public screens and that ScreenBacker be running if you
wish to add backdrops or menus to public screens. It will launch those
programs automatically if needed, however, you may need to tell it
where to find them if they are not in its search path: see the @{"DAEMON" link DAEMONNode}
and @{"BACKER" BACKERNode} tooltypes.@{par}

The following disk-based Commodore libraries are required, but are
part of AmigaOS 2.04 (and later releases) anyway:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} asl.library V37 or higher. @{i}(requesters)@{ui}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} rexxsyslib.library V36 or higher. @{i}(ARexx support)@{ui}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} commodities.library V37 or higher. @{i}(commodity support)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

The following disk-based libraries are optional, but their absence
will limit the functionality of ScreenMaster:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} locale.library V38 or higher. @{i}(localization)@{ui}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} diskfont.library V36 or higher. @{i}(custom font support)@{ui}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} iffparse.library V37 or higher. @{i}(backdrop patterns, etc)@{ui}@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} amigaguide.library V33 or higher. @{i}(on-line help)@{ui}@{line}
@{lindent 0}

Additionally, ScreenDaemon and ScreenBacker will use the ReqTools
library (V38 or higher) for their requesters, if it's available.@{par}

Neither BGUI nor MUI are included. Both are available from AmiNet
(directories dev/gui and util/libs), or any good PD supplier. ReqTools
is also not included, but is optional anyway.@{par}

@endnode

