@remark *********************************************************************

@node StartingNode "ScreenMaster: Starting and Quitting"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Starting and Quitting@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=====================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

To start any of the programs, double click on the program's icon, or
run the program from a Shell. As both ScreenDaemon and ScreenBacker
work in the background, it makes sense to use "Run >NIL:" when
starting them from a Shell.@{par}

All of the programs except the BGUI version of ScreenMenuEd are
commodities, so you can quit them using the Exchange program. If the
program opens a window, you can also select the 'Quit' button or menu
item.@{par}

Alternatively, you can stop either of the daemons, and the BGUI
versions of ScreenMaster and ScreenMenuEd, by sending them a Control-C
signal using the AmigaDOS "Break" command.@{par}

Note that neither ScreenDaemon nor ScreenBacker will be able to quit
if they are still in charge of a public screen.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node MasterWindowNode "ScreenMaster: The ScreenMaster Window"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}The ScreenMaster Window@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=======================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

When ScreenMaster starts up it opens a small window listing all the
available public screens. The system default public screen is
indicated in @{b}bold@{ub}, public screens which are currently private
are listed in @{i}italics@{ui}.@{par}

The gadgets in ScreenMaster's window are:@{par}

@{b}@{fg shine}Open@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

To open a new public screen. The @{"Open New Public Screen" link OpenPubScrNode} window will
open with gadgets for specifying the properties of the new screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Close@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Closes the selected public screen. This will not be possible if the
screen is currently private, or if the screen has visitor windows open
on it. The ScreenMaster window does not count as a visitor in this
case.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Jump@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Moves ScreenMaster's window to the selected screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Info@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Displays, in a requester, a summary of the properties of the selected
screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Refresh@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Refreshes ScreenMaster's list of public screens. This is necessary if
another application opens or closes a public screen, independantly
of ScreenMaster.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Default@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Makes the selected screen the system default public screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}PopPub@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

When this is checked, visitor windows opening on a public screen will
cause that screen to be 'popped' to the front.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Shanghai@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}--------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

When this is checked, Intuition will force older programs that try to
open windows on the Workbench screen onto the default public screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Hide@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} Iconifies ScreenMaster on the Workbench screen. Double click the
icon, or select "Show" in the Exchange program to uniconify it.
Alternatively, you can define an iconify hotkey in the MUI Preferences
program and use that.@{par}

@{i}BGUI:@{ui} Closes ScreenMaster's window but keeps it in memory as a
commodity. Reopen the window by selecting "Show" in the Exchange
program, or using the hotkey you defined with the CX_POPKEY tooltype.
@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Quit@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Closes ScreenMaster's window and removes it from memory. Both
ScreenDaemon and ScreenBacker will continue running if they have been
launched.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node MasterMenusNode "ScreenMaster: ScreenMaster's Menu Items"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}ScreenMaster's Menu Items@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=========================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

ScreenMaster has only one menu, titled "Project" and these are the
items in it:@{par}

@{b}@{fg shine}Open...@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

To open a new public screen. The @{"Open New Public Screen" link OpenPubScrNode} window will
open with gadgets for specifying the properties of the new screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Default@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Makes the selected screen the system default public screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Close@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Closes the selected public screen. This will not be possible if the
screen is currently private, or if the screen has visitor windows open
on it. The ScreenMaster window does not count as a visitor in this
case.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Jump@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Moves ScreenMaster's window to the selected screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Info...@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Displays, in a requester, a summary of the properties of the selected
screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Refresh@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Refreshes ScreenMaster's list of public screens. This is necessary if
another application opens or closes a public screen, independantly
of ScreenMaster.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Help...@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Opens ScreenMaster's AmigaGuide documentation. If the guide is not in
AmigaGuide's search path, tell ScreenMaster where to find it using the
GUIDENAME tooltype.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}About...@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}--------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Opens a requester showing information about ScreenMaster.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Hide@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} Iconifies ScreenMaster on the Workbench screen. Double click the
icon, or select "Show" in the Exchange program to uniconify it.
Alternatively, you can define an iconify hotkey in the MUI Preferences
program and use that.@{par}

@{i}BGUI:@{ui} Closes ScreenMaster's window but keeps it in memory as a
commodity. Reopen the window by selecting "Show" in the Exchange
program, or using the hotkey you defined with the CX_POPKEY tooltype.
@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Quit@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Closes ScreenMaster's window and removes it from memory. Both
ScreenDaemon and ScreenBacker will continue running if they have been
launched.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node OpenPubScrNode "Opening a New Public Screen"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Opening a New Public Screen@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===========================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

When you select the Open button gadget in ScreenMaster's window the
Open New Public Screen window appears, allowing you to set the
characteristics of the new public screen. This window has two pages of
gadgets: the Screen page and the Options page.@{par}

@{code}
  @{"The Screen Page.  " link ScreenPageNode}
  @{"The Options Page. " link OptionsPageNode}
@{body}

Always present underneath these pages are these three buttons:@{par}

@{b}@{fg shine}Open@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Opens a new public screen with the properties specified. ScreenDaemon
will be launched if it is not already running, and ScreenBacker as
well, if you have asked for a backdrop or menu. If it opens
successfully, ScreenMaster will move its window to the new screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Save As@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

With this button you can save the specification of the screen as an
ARexx script. ScreenMaster will open a file requester for you to
specify the name of the script, and will also save a project icon for
it.@{par}

The project icon used by default is "def_ScreenMaster" but you can
override this with the AREXXICON tooltype. The default tool property
of the icon, if blank, is set to "SYS:Rexxc/RX", so you can simply
double click on the icon to start the script and open the screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Abandons the opening of a new public screen and closes the window.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node ScreenPageNode "ScreenMaster: Open New Public Screen: Screen Page"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Open New Public Screen: Screen Page@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===================================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

These are the gadgets on the Screen page of the Open New Public Screen
window:@{par}

@{b}@{fg shine}Name@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Supply a name for the new public screen. This must be unique. Bear in
mind that with most operations, the name is case-sensitive: there is a
difference between lower and upper case. Although not necessary, it is
recommended that you avoid using spaces in the name.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Title@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

The screen title. If omitted, the public screen name will be used.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Display Mode@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}------------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Select a display mode from the list. Only Workbench-compatible modes
available on your system are listed. @{i}BGUI:@{ui} You can use the up/down
cursor keys to select from this list.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}All Modes@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}---------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

If you select this checkbox, the display modes list will include all
Workbench-compatible modes regardless of whether they are actually
obtainable with your hardware. Trying to open a screen in a mode not
available with your system will simply elicit an error message.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Colours@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Set the slider to the desired number of colours for the new public
screen. @{i}BGUI:@{ui} You can control this slider with the left/right cursor
keys, as well.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Width and Height@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Generally you would accept the default width and height for a given
mode, but if you deselect the appropriate Default checkbox, you can
override this and enter your desired value for the width or height in
one of the integer gadgets supplied. You may need to make appropriate
selections for Overscan and AutoScroll on the Options page.@{par}


See also: @{"The Options Page" link OptionsPageNode}@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node OptionsPageNode "ScreenMaster: Open New Public Screen: Options Page"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Open New Public Screen: Options Page@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}====================================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

These are the gadgets on the Options page of the Open New Public
Screen window:@{par}

@{b}@{fg shine}Overscan@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}--------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Select an overscan setting for the new screen. The first two options,
Text and Graphics, are those set by you using the Overscan preferences
program. Alternatively, you can select Custom and then enter your own
coordinates into the DisplayClip gadget below.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}DispClip@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}--------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

This gadget is only enabled if you choose Custom overscan. Enter four
integers, separated by commas, as the coordinates of the visible area
of the screen, in the order MinX, MinY, MaxX and MaxY. For example,
"-8,-4,655,519". You will probably want to specify a non-standard
width and height for the screen as well - see the @{"Screen" link ScreenPageNode} page.@{par}

@{fg highlight}*WARNING!* Be careful with this facility! I'm not sure how much error
checking the AmigaOS does on these values, but you just might be able
to damage your Amiga and/or your monitor by using out of range values!@{fg text}@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}SysPens@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

You can specify the colour pens that Intuition should use for screen
items like text, highlight, background, etc. Select a pen type from
the cycle gadget and enter the pen number in the integer gadget. For a
custom pen selection take effect, you must leave the cycle gadget on
an option other than "Use Default".@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Font Type@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}---------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Three options are provided for the screen font. "System" uses the
system default monospace font and "Screen" selects the system
preferred font. The actual font used for both of these can be set with
the Font preferences program.@{par}

Alternatively, select the "Custom" option and pick your own font
using the Pick Font gadget below.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Pick Font@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}---------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

This gadget is only enabled when Font Type, above, is set to "Custom".
Type in the name and size of your preferred font, using the format
"fontname/size", for example "Times/15". Alternatively, clicking on
the button to the right of this gadget opens a font requester for you
to make your choice with.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Palette@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Type in the name of an IFF ILBM picture file or Workbench palette
preferences file with the desired palette. You can press the button to
the right to pick one using a file requester. If the Palette gadget is
blank, the new screen will get the Workbench colour palette, as set
with the Palette preferences program. Note that ScreenMaster will
extract the palette information from a Workbench 3 preferences file,
but not the system pen assignments.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Pattern@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

If you wish the new screen to have a backdrop pattern, enter the name
of the Workbench pattern file or IFF ILBM picture. Pressing the button
to the right elicits a file requester for making your choice. You may
also need to change the settings of the PatternTile and Pat.Centre
gadgets. ScreenMaster doesn't do any fancy pen remapping, so you
should make sure the screen's palette is suitable for the backdrop.
Note that, if given a Workbench 3 pattern preferences file,
ScreenMaster will use only the screen pattern recorded in it (ie. not
the Workbench window or drawer window patterns).@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Menu@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

If you would like to add a custom menu definition to the new public
screen, type its name in here, or press the button to the right to get
a file requester that you can pick one with. The Add Menu checkbox
must be selected for this gadget to be enabled.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}AutoScroll@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Normally you would leave this checked, so that screens larger than the
visible display area scroll automatically when you move the mouse
pointer to the edge. Deselect this checkbox if for some reason you
don't want this behaviour.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Interleaved@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-----------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Available only under AmigaOS V39 and higher, selecting this checkbox
causes the new screen to open with an interleaved bitmap, if possible.
This reduces flicker on screens with many colours.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}SharePens@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}---------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Available only under AmigaOS V39 and higher, selecting this checkbox
asks Intuition to leave the non-system pens of the new screen
unallocated. This gives applications that open on this screen more
freedom to manipulate the screen's colours.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}OpenBehind@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

If this checkbox is selected, the new screen will open behind all
other screens. This can be useful within ARexx scripts, where you can
send the TOFRONT command to ScreenDaemon when you want the screen
brought to the front. If this checkbox is selected, ScreenMaster will
not jump to the new screen when it's opened.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}AutoClose@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}---------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

If this checkbox is selected, the new screen will close as soon as all
visitor windows on it have closed. Be aware that the ScreenMaster
window is counted as a visitor in this case, so you might need to use
the OpenBehind option as well.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}PatternTile@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-----------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

If you want the backdrop pattern specified by the pattern gadget to be
repeated across and down the screen, select this checkbox.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Pat.Centre@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

If you want the backdrop pattern specified by the pattern gadget to be
centred in the middle of the screen, select this checkbox.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}Add Menu@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}--------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

If this checkbox is selected, ScreenMaster will ask ScreenBacker to
attach a menu to the new screen. This menu has a few screen management
functions in it, but you can extend it with a custom menu definition
file, created by hand or with ScreenMenuEd. To use a custom menu,
select this checkbox and put the name of the menu definition file in
the Menu gadget to the left.@{par}


See also: @{"The Screen Page" link ScreenPageNode}@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node TooltypesNode "ScreenMaster: Tooltypes and Shell Arguments"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Tooltypes and Shell Arguments@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=============================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

All the programs in the ScreenMaster suite can be configured using
tooltypes or Shell arguments. The tooltypes of ScreenMaster itself are
described here; see the appropriate sections of the other guides for
the tooltypes of the other programs:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{" ScreenDaemon Tooltypes " link "ScreenDaemon.guide/TooltypesNode"}@{line}
@{" ScreenBacker Tooltypes " link "ScreenBacker.guide/TooltypesNode"}@{line}
@{" ScreenMenuEd Tooltypes " link "ScreenMenuEd.guide/TooltypesNode"}@{par}
@{lindent 0}

@{b}@{fg shine}ScreenMaster Tooltypes@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

The tooltypes ScreenMaster looks for in its program icon are described
below. The arguments used from a Shell are identical, except where
stated otherwise. The full Shell template (with abbreviations) is:

@{code}
@{i}BGUI:@{ui}
           PS=PUBSCREEN/K, AI=AREXXICON/K, GN=GUIDENAME/K,
       LA=LANGUAGE/K, DA=DAEMON/K, BA=BACKER/K, RI=READICON/S,
          PU=CX_POPUP/S, PK=CX_POPKEY/K, PR=CX_PRIORITY/K/N,
          SW=SAVEWINSIZE/S, WF=WINDOWFONT/K, ML=MINLIST/K/N

@{i}MUI:@{ui}
           PS=PUBSCREEN/K, AI=AREXXICON/K, GN=GUIDENAME/K,
        LA=LANGUAGE/K, DA=DAEMON/K, BA=BACKER/K, RI=READICON/S
@{body}

ScreenMaster's tooltypes consist of three kinds:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{b}String@{ub} - You must supply a string of some kind; a filename,
public screen name, etc. For example, "LANGUAGE=deutsch".@{par}

@{b}Integer@{ub} - You must supply a numeric value (a whole number).
For example, "MINLIST=5".@{par}

@{b}Boolean@{ub} - In tooltypes you must supply one of the following: YES, NO,
TRUE or FALSE. For example, "CX_POPUP=YES". You can also omit the
value entirely, which indicates the YES or TRUE state. On a Shell
command line, just state the keyword without a value to get the TRUE
state, omit the keyword for FALSE.@{par}
@{lindent 0}

@{code}
@{i}BGUI and MUI:@{ui}

    Tooltype         Type     Short Description
    ------------     ----     --------------------------------------
    @{"PUBSCREEN  " link PUBSCREENNode  }     STR      Name of public screen to open on.
    @{"AREXXICON  " link AREXXICONNode  }     STR      Project icon for ARexx scripts.
    @{"GUIDENAME  " link GUIDENAMENode  }     STR      Where to find ScreenMaster.guide.
    @{"LANGUAGE   " link LANGUAGENode   }     STR      Specify language catalog.
    @{"DAEMON     " link DAEMONNode     }     STR      Location of ScreenDaemon.
    @{"BACKER     " link BACKERNode     }     STR      Location of ScreenBacker.
    @{"READICON   " link READICONNode   }     BOOL     Read config. from tooltypes (Shell).

@{i}BGUI only:@{ui}

    Tooltype         Type     Short Description
    ------------     ----     --------------------------------------
    @{"CX_POPUP   " link CX_POPUPNode   }     BOOL     Whether to open window on start up.
    @{"CX_POPKEY  " link CX_POPKEYNode  }     STR      Commodities popup hotkey definition.
    @{"CX_PRIORITY" link CX_PRIORITYNode}     INT      Priority of hotkey among commodities.
    @{"SAVEWINSIZE" link SAVEWINSIZENode}     BOOL     Save window size/position on exit.
    @{"WINDOWFONT " link WINDOWFONTNode }     STR      Font to use in window.
    @{"MINLIST    " link MINLISTNode    }     INT      Minimum entries in public screen list.
@{body}

In the MUI version, options equivalent to CX_POPUP, CX_POPKEY and
WINDOWFONT can be set using the MUI Preferences program. The other
options are either not applicable, or unavailable.@{par}

If you put ScreenMaster in your WBStartUp drawer, you should add the
tooltype "DONOTWAIT" so Workbench won't wait for ScreenMaster to quit
before continuing with its start up.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node PUBSCREENNode "ScreenMaster: PUBSCREEN Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}PUBSCREEN@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      String
Default:   <system default>
Shell:     PS=PUBSCREEN/K
Tooltype:  PUBSCREEN
@{body}

The name of the public screen that ScreenMaster should initially open
its window on. If omitted, ScreenMaster opens on the default public
screen, which is normally Workbench, or in the case of the MUI
version, on the screen specified using the MUI Preferences program. Be
aware that public screen names are case-sensitive, ie. "MyScreen" is
not the same as "MYSCREEN".@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node AREXXICONNode "ScreenMaster: AREXXICON Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}AREXXICON@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      String
Default:   def_ScreenMaster
Shell:     AI=AREXXICON/K
Tooltype:  AREXXICON
@{body}

Use this tooltype to tell ScreenMaster what project icon to use when
saving screen specifications as ARexx scripts. If the default tool of
this icon is blank, ScreenMaster will set it to "SYS:Rexxc/RX" for all
icons it saves.@{par}

If you set AREXXICON to the special value "NONE", no project icon will
be saved with ARexx scripts.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node GUIDENAMENode "ScreenMaster: GUIDENAME Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}GUIDENAME@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      String
Default:   ScreenMaster.guide
Shell:     GN=GUIDENAME/K
Tooltype:  GUIDENAME
@{body}

If ScreenMaster.guide is not on AmigaGuide's search path, set this
tooltype to the pathname of this guide so that on-line help is
available.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node LANGUAGENode "ScreenMaster: LANGUAGE Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}LANGUAGE@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      String
Default:   <system default>
Shell:     LA=LANGUAGE/K
Tooltype:  LANGUAGE
@{body}

ScreenMaster supports the locale library of AmigaOS 2.1 and above,
allowing it to display text and messages in your preferred language.
You would normally specify the language with the Locale Preferences
program; this tooltype allows you to override that setting if
necessary.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node DAEMONNode "ScreenMaster: DAEMON Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}DAEMON@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}======@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      String
Default:   ScreenDaemon
Shell:     DA=DAEMON/K
Tooltype:  DAEMON
@{body}

If ScreenDaemon isn't running when you ask ScreenMaster to open a
public screen, ScreenMaster will try to launch the daemon
automatically. If the daemon is in ScreenMaster's search path this
will work, otherwise use this tooltype to tell ScreenMaster where to
find it.@{par}

I recommend you add the READICON keyword as well, so that the daemon
when started, reads its configuration from its tooltypes. For example:
"DAEMON=Work:Things/ScreenDaemon READICON".@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node BACKERNode "ScreenMaster: BACKER Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}BACKER@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}======@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      String
Default:   ScreenBacker
Shell:     BA=BACKER/K
Tooltype:  BACKER
@{body}

If ScreenBacker isn't running when you ask ScreenMaster to open a
public screen with a backdrop or menu, ScreenMaster will try to launch
ScreenBacker automatically. If ScreenBacker is in ScreenMaster's
search path this will work, otherwise use this tooltype to tell
ScreenMaster where to find it.@{par}

I recommend you add the READICON keyword as well so that ScreenBacker,
when started, reads its configuration from its tooltypes. For example:
"BACKER=Work:Things/ScreenBacker READICON".@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node READICONNode "ScreenMaster: READICON Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}READICON@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI and MUI
Type:      Boolean
Default:   FALSE
Shell:     RI=READICON/S
Tooltype:  <not applicable>
@{body}

This keyword is only available from the Shell command line. It makes
ScreenMaster read its configuration from its icon's tooltypes rather
than the command line. This is useful in conjunction with program
launchers that run programs as if from a Shell. Ordinarily you would
have to duplicate all your preferred ScreenMaster configuration
arguments in the command that you supply to the launcher, but by
specifying READICON, you can keep your settings in the icon.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node CX_POPUPNode "ScreenMaster: CX_POPUP Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}CX_POPUP@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI only
Type:      Boolean
Default:   FALSE
Shell:     PU=CX_POPUP/S
Tooltype:  CX_POPUP
@{body}

ScreenMaster's default behaviour is to start without opening its
window. You can then use the Exchange program, or a suitably defined
popup hotkey (see the @{"CX_POPKEY" link CX_POPKEYNode} tooltype), to wake it up. This makes
sense if you put ScreenMaster in your WBStartup drawer.@{par}

If you set this tooltype to TRUE, however, it will open its window
immediately, which is more sensible for interactive use.@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} The "Start Iconified" option in the MUI Preferences program has a
similar function to this option.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node CX_POPKEYNode "ScreenMaster: CX_POPKEY Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}CX_POPKEY@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI only
Type:      String
Default:   <none>
Shell:     PK=CX_POPKEY/K
Tooltype:  CX_POPKEY
@{body}

If you would like to able to re-open ScreenMaster's window with a key
combination when it is hidden, set this tooltype to a valid hotkey
definition. See your Amiga manuals for the syntax of these.@{par}

Note that ScreenMaster always registers itself as a commodity anyway,
so can always be re-opened using the Exchange program.@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} The "Iconify Hotkey" option in the MUI Preferences program has a
similar function to this option.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node CX_PRIORITYNode "ScreenMaster: CX_PRIORITY Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}CX_PRIORITY@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI only
Type:      Integer
Default:   0
Shell:     PR=CX_PRIORITY/K/N
Tooltype:  CX_PRIORITY
@{body}

Use this tooltype to set ScreenMaster's priority relative to the other
commodities running. Normally there is no need to change this.@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} This option is unavailable.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node SAVEWINSIZENode "ScreenMaster: SAVEWINSIZE Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}SAVEWINSIZE@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI only
Type:      Boolean
Default:   FALSE
Shell:     SW=SAVEWINSIZE/S
Tooltype:  SAVEWINSIZE
@{body}

ScreenMaster normally opens its window centred under the mouse pointer
If, however, you would like the window to open with a particular size
and position each time, set the SAVEWINSIZE tooltype to TRUE.@{par}

This will cause ScreenMaster to save the window co-ordinates to a
small file called "ScreenMaster.win" in the ENV: directory each time
the program quits. Every time you start ScreenMaster, it will read and
re-use this window definition.@{par}

Once you have positioned the window as you like it, quit ScreenMaster,
unset the SAVEWINSIZE tooltype, and copy the "ScreenMaster.win" file
from ENV: to ENVARC:. It will then be copied back to ENV: by the
standard Startup-Sequence each time you boot your Amiga.@{par}

However, if ScreenMaster's window opens on a screen with a larger
font, the window will expand to fit it, regardless of any saved
settings.@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} The MUI system automatically remembers the window's size and
position.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node WINDOWFONTNode "ScreenMaster: WINDOWFONT Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}WINDOWFONT@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}==========@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI only
Type:      String
Default:   <screen default>
Shell:     WF=WINDOWFONT/K
Tooltype:  WINDOWFONT
@{body}

ScreenMaster normally uses the default font of the screen it opens on.
If you wish to override this setting, specify the font with this
tooltype, using the following format: "example.font/12", where the 12
indicates the desired point size.@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} The "Fonts" page in the MUI Preferences program provides a
facility similar to this option.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node MINLISTNode "ScreenMaster: MINLIST Keyword"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}MINLIST@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=======@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}
@{code}
Versions:  BGUI only
Type:      Integer
Default:   3
Shell:     ML=MINLIST/K/N
Tooltype:  MINLIST
@{body}

The minimum number of entries shown in ScreenMaster's list of public
screens is normally 3; you can't size the window any smaller. By
giving this tooltype a higher value, you can increase the minimum
number of entries shown at all times, though this will make the window
taller.@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} This option is unavailable.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node CommandsNode "ScreenMaster: ARexx Commands"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}ScreenMaster ARexx Commands@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}===========================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

For details of the ARexx commands provided by @{"ScreenDaemon" link "ScreenDaemon.guide/CommandsNode"} and
@{"ScreenBacker" link "ScreenBacker.guide/CommandsNode"}, see the appropriate section of their guides.@{par}

ScreenMaster has an ARexx port called "SCREENMASTER". It understands
the following commands:@{par}

@{b}@{fg shine}JUMP <psname>@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Moves ScreenMaster's window to the named public screen, bringing that
screen to the front and activating the window. If the window is closed
when this command is given, it will be opened on that screen.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}REFRESH@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Makes ScreenMaster refresh its list of public screens as well as the
state of the PopPub and Shanghai checkboxes. Effective even when
ScreenMaster's window is closed, but does not cause the window to
open.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}SHOW@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

@{i}BGUI:@{ui} Opens ScreenMaster's window on the screen it was last on, if
possible. If the window is already open, moves it to the front and
activates it.@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} Uniconifies ScreenMaster, opening its window on the screen it was
last on, if possible. If the window is already open, moves it to the
front and activates it.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}HIDE@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

@{i}BGUI:@{ui} Closes ScreenMaster's window. Has no effect if the window is
already closed.@{par}

@{i}MUI:@{ui} Iconifies ScreenMaster's window. Has no effect if ScreenMaster is
already iconified.@{par}


@{b}@{fg shine}QUIT@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}----@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Quits ScreenMaster. ScreenDaemon and ScreenBacker continue to run, if
launched.@{par}

@endnode

@remark *********************************************************************

@node BugsNode "ScreenMaster: Bugs and Improvements"
@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}Bugs and Improvements@{fg text}@{ub}@{line}
@{b}@{fg shine}=====================@{fg text}@{ub}@{par}

Known Bugs and Limitations:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} None.@{line}
@{lindent 0}

Suggested improvements in no particular order:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Master/Daemon: Reading system pen assignments in V39+ palette prefs
files.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Master/Backer: Choice of which pattern to use from a V39+ pattern
file.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Backer: Colour remapping and pen acquisition for backdrops under
V39+ - use datatypes to load backdrop images.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Master: Copy default screen attributes when opening the Open New
Public Screen window.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Master: Option for timed, automatic refresh of public screens list
and flags.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Master/Daemon: Option to close Workbench screen.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Daemon/Backer: Return error messages or codes as secondary ARexx
results.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Daemon/Backer: Put requesters up using a separate thread, so that
ARexx commands can still be processed.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Master/Daemon: Support for OS3 "SA_LikeWorkbench" tag.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Daemon: ARexx commands to get info like lists of public screens,
attributes of a named screen, etc.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Master/MenuEd: Make AmigaGuide on-line help asynchronous.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} General: A new utility, ScreenDirector, that patches OpenWindow()
and redirects user-specified applications onto pre-defined public
screens.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} General: Use OS3 memory pools.@{line}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} General: Some catalogs!@{line}
@{lindent 0}

Please send bug reports or further suggestions to @{"me" link AuthorNode}.
Enforcer testing would be particularly valuable, as I have no MMU.@{par}

Bug reports must include the following information:@{par}
@{lindent 2}

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Your Amiga model and processor;@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Kickstart and Workbench versions;@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Chip and Fast memory sizes;@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} ScreenMaster version;@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} BGUI or MUI version;@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Whether the bug is consistent (happens every time) or intermittent
(just once in a while);@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} A clear explanation of what is required to reproduce the problem,
and its effects (Guru meditation numbers, Enforcer hit reports, etc);@{line}
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Whether the problem appears when booting without patches, other
commodities, etc.@{line}
@{lindent 0}

@endnode

